1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:11,640
The U.S. is in the midst of a reading crisis, and our nation can't afford to sugarcoat it.

2
00:00:11,640 --> 00:00:15,120
Things are bad, really bad.

3
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:22,400
But a vast body of research called the Science of Reading can tell us how to fix it.

4
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:28,760
According to the NAEP, the nation's report card, 66% of American fourth graders are failing

5
00:00:28,760 --> 00:00:33,799
to meet the proficiency level on the National Reading Assessment.

6
00:00:33,799 --> 00:00:40,119
That means that if the U.S. were an average-sized classroom of 25 students, about 17 children

7
00:00:40,119 --> 00:00:42,400
are below proficient.

8
00:00:42,400 --> 00:00:48,200
And these shockingly low early childhood literacy rates are not equally dispersed.

9
00:00:48,200 --> 00:00:53,320
About 82% of black fourth graders fall below proficiency.

10
00:00:53,880 --> 00:01:00,680
Meanwhile, childhood literacy is one of the most important predictors of future life outcomes.

11
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:05,000
Children with below-basic reading skills in third grade are six times as likely to fail

12
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,440
finishing high school in time.

13
00:01:07,440 --> 00:01:14,599
And 70% of incarcerated adults are unable to read above a fourth grade level.

14
00:01:14,599 --> 00:01:16,680
But there's a silver lining.

15
00:01:16,680 --> 00:01:19,360
We know how to fix this one.

16
00:01:19,360 --> 00:01:24,839
In this video, we'll tell you what steps America must take as soon as possible to ensure

17
00:01:24,839 --> 00:01:31,959
that every child in every zip code has equitable access to the world through literacy.

18
00:01:31,959 --> 00:01:38,400
In 2013, the state of Mississippi ranked 49th out of 50 states in childhood literacy rates.

19
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:42,879
But over the next decade, something astonishing happened.

20
00:01:42,879 --> 00:01:49,279
Mississippi's literacy rates skyrocketed from second worst all the way to 21st out of 50 states.

21
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:53,440
The press labeled this event the Mississippi Miracle.

22
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:57,040
That's what people are calling the dramatic shift in reading scores accomplished by the

23
00:01:57,040 --> 00:01:58,839
state of Mississippi.

24
00:01:58,839 --> 00:02:00,440
But this was no miracle.

25
00:02:00,440 --> 00:02:04,360
This was good policy and good reading science.

26
00:02:04,360 --> 00:02:09,360
Mississippi decided to let go of a very popular, well-marketed, but largely ineffective way

27
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:14,559
to teach reading, replacing it with an approach that science of reading researchers have advocated

28
00:02:14,559 --> 00:02:17,000
for for decades.

29
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,479
Let's talk about those two approaches.

30
00:02:19,479 --> 00:02:26,160
Chapter one, conflicting ideas about reading, meaning-based versus code-based.

31
00:02:26,160 --> 00:02:30,000
For many years, there have been two conflicting ideas about how children should be taught

32
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:31,000
to read.

33
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:36,360
The first, meaning-based approaches, are the methods Mississippi largely used up until

34
00:02:36,360 --> 00:02:38,759
2013.

35
00:02:38,759 --> 00:02:43,000
Meaning-based approaches assume that reading skills are best acquired naturally through

36
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:48,600
context and immersion, much like when children begin to speak their native language.

37
00:02:48,600 --> 00:02:52,759
Meaning-based perspectives are sometimes called top-down because they encourage students to

38
00:02:52,759 --> 00:02:59,720
guess or predict the meaning of words based on context, pictures, and existing knowledge.

39
00:02:59,720 --> 00:03:04,039
Consider this example from the popular three-queuing approach to reading.

40
00:03:04,039 --> 00:03:08,320
Students are told to ask themselves three questions, or cues, before taking a guess

41
00:03:08,320 --> 00:03:10,160
at the correct word.

42
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:11,679
Does it make sense?

43
00:03:11,679 --> 00:03:13,360
Does it sound right?

44
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:15,160
Does it look right?

45
00:03:15,160 --> 00:03:20,080
And the children must then predict what the appropriate word might be.

46
00:03:20,080 --> 00:03:25,720
Widespread meaning-based approaches like three-queuing, Marie Clay's balanced literacy, and whole

47
00:03:25,720 --> 00:03:30,080
language learning all operate on the same fundamental premise, that students should

48
00:03:30,080 --> 00:03:35,119
learn reading naturally, just like how they learned spoken language for the first time.

49
00:03:35,119 --> 00:03:39,679
Over the decades, meaning-based approaches spread across the country like wildfire, thanks

50
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:44,479
largely to impressive marketing campaigns emphasizing their ability to kindle a child's

51
00:03:44,479 --> 00:03:46,880
natural love of reading.

52
00:03:46,880 --> 00:03:50,559
But there is a major problem with meaning-based approaches.

53
00:03:50,559 --> 00:03:55,479
Children cannot learn to love reading if they are never properly taught how to read in the

54
00:03:55,479 --> 00:03:56,919
first place.

55
00:03:56,919 --> 00:04:02,080
Which brings us to the second idea about reading, the one Mississippi systematically adopted

56
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:04,320
in 2013.

57
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:09,160
Proponents of code-based approaches have long maintained that learning how to read is not

58
00:04:09,160 --> 00:04:11,520
at all like learning to speak.

59
00:04:11,520 --> 00:04:15,440
In the code-based view, the proper analogy for learning to read is more like learning

60
00:04:15,440 --> 00:04:17,679
how to play a new instrument.

61
00:04:17,679 --> 00:04:22,320
You've got to start with the basics, get the fundamentals down, and with time and practice,

62
00:04:22,320 --> 00:04:24,320
you'll play beautifully.

63
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:29,320
Through code-based instruction, letter-sound relationships are taught explicitly.

64
00:04:29,320 --> 00:04:35,279
Structured literacy emphasizes the structure of language through phonology, sound-symbol

65
00:04:35,279 --> 00:04:43,440
association, syllables, morphology, syntax, and semantics.

66
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:48,519
Rather than a top-down game of prediction based on what a learner already knows, code-based

67
00:04:48,519 --> 00:04:51,239
methods are bottom-up.

68
00:04:51,239 --> 00:04:53,640
Start at the beginning and build up.

69
00:04:53,640 --> 00:04:58,640
Disagreements around these entrenched ideas about reading intensified over the decades,

70
00:04:58,640 --> 00:05:03,920
reaching a boiling point in the 80s and 90s when the dispute was finally given a name,

71
00:05:03,920 --> 00:05:05,880
the Reading Wars.

72
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:11,040
The Reading Wars raged for decades, but it was only ever an ideological debate.

73
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:14,200
The science was always clear.

74
00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:15,640
Chapter 2.

75
00:05:15,640 --> 00:05:16,640
What the Research Says

76
00:05:16,640 --> 00:05:21,760
Today, that science is clearer than ever.

77
00:05:21,760 --> 00:05:26,200
Human brains are not wired to read and write, and meaning-based approaches do not work well

78
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:28,279
for most students.

79
00:05:28,279 --> 00:05:33,480
Cognitive scientists agree that human brains process written language letter by letter,

80
00:05:33,480 --> 00:05:37,480
word by sound, and the research shows that students perform much better when they are

81
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:39,799
taught code-based approaches.

82
00:05:39,799 --> 00:05:44,720
Without code-based instruction, many students will continue to struggle, lost in a wilderness

83
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:47,200
of letters and words.

84
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:51,839
The science of reading has demonstrated that 95% of children have the ability to learn

85
00:05:51,839 --> 00:05:53,000
to read.

86
00:05:53,000 --> 00:06:00,079
But to do it effectively, up to 50% of those children require careful, systematic instruction.

87
00:06:00,079 --> 00:06:05,200
A structured literacy approach is a necessary foundation for reading success, consistent

88
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:07,839
with code-based approaches.

89
00:06:07,839 --> 00:06:12,480
Structured literacy begins by helping children understand the building blocks of language,

90
00:06:12,480 --> 00:06:16,359
allowing the readers to master the structure of sentences.

91
00:06:16,359 --> 00:06:23,279
Structured literacy is systematic, it's cumulative, it's explicit, and it's diagnostic.

92
00:06:23,279 --> 00:06:28,399
Understanding how sounds come together to form words is the key to unlocking reading.

93
00:06:28,399 --> 00:06:34,640
When students have the key, they can explore a vast wilderness of words, books, and ideas.

94
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:39,239
A whole new world of possibilities and opportunities.

95
00:06:39,239 --> 00:06:40,679
Chapter 3.

96
00:06:40,679 --> 00:06:43,440
How in the world did we get here?

97
00:06:43,440 --> 00:06:48,119
How did meaning-based approaches like whole language, balanced literacy, and 3Qing come

98
00:06:48,119 --> 00:06:50,799
to dominate the American educational system?

99
00:06:50,799 --> 00:06:55,279
And how could we have gotten this so wrong for so long?

100
00:06:55,279 --> 00:06:57,399
There are four major reasons.

101
00:06:57,399 --> 00:07:00,799
First, powerful business incentives.

102
00:07:00,799 --> 00:07:05,000
Well-resourced publishing companies with strong marketing departments offered schools engaging

103
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:09,959
books and resources, and developed highly attractive sales strategies.

104
00:07:09,959 --> 00:07:13,720
While it isn't possible to know whether the authors and publishers of meaning-based methods

105
00:07:13,720 --> 00:07:19,359
knowingly promoted inaccurate reading methods, at best, they knew the scientific evidence

106
00:07:19,359 --> 00:07:22,959
was out there, and they avoided investigating it.

107
00:07:22,959 --> 00:07:27,079
Sadly, their negligence caused significant harm.

108
00:07:27,079 --> 00:07:31,679
Second, the science public disconnect.

109
00:07:31,679 --> 00:07:36,480
Scientists have long understood the pedagogical superiority of code-based instruction, but

110
00:07:36,480 --> 00:07:38,920
they struggled to reach decision makers.

111
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:43,279
Meanwhile, the public was made to believe that the reading wars were a conflict between

112
00:07:43,279 --> 00:07:49,079
two legitimate sides, because they didn't see or know about the science.

113
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Third, institutional barriers.

114
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:58,640
Thanks to a range of institutional barriers, even today, only 25% of teacher education

115
00:07:58,640 --> 00:08:03,320
programs include findings from the science of reading research and structured literacy

116
00:08:03,320 --> 00:08:06,720
instructional approaches.

117
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:09,079
And fourth, the tree of trust.

118
00:08:09,079 --> 00:08:14,679
Parents, teachers, and even most administrators aren't to blame in this story.

119
00:08:14,679 --> 00:08:19,040
Because teachers relied on teacher expertise, teachers understandably trusted their school

120
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:26,760
districts, and districts deferred to extremely convincing publishers and authors.

121
00:08:26,760 --> 00:08:28,000
Chapter 4.

122
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,519
The Science of Reading Revolution.

123
00:08:30,519 --> 00:08:36,320
Thankfully, in recent years, a wave of change has swept across the nation.

124
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:41,320
Thirty states have made key legal changes, aiming to bridge the gap between the science

125
00:08:41,320 --> 00:08:43,080
and the classroom.

126
00:08:43,080 --> 00:08:48,000
Many have also begun banning meaning-based approaches like 3-Q-ing, but this is just

127
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,359
the beginning.

128
00:08:49,359 --> 00:08:54,000
In order to provide access to the code for all children, districts must follow the example

129
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:55,919
set by Mississippi.

130
00:08:55,919 --> 00:09:00,359
Specifically, districts must develop a multi-year literacy plan.

131
00:09:00,359 --> 00:09:06,799
This plan must adopt proven structured literacy programming, prioritize teacher training,

132
00:09:06,799 --> 00:09:12,359
empowering and arming teachers with knowledge and tools, implement universal screening to

133
00:09:12,359 --> 00:09:18,119
identify reading challenges early, create a tiered system of student support so that

134
00:09:18,119 --> 00:09:21,840
all children receive the resources they need.

135
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:23,320
That is the answer.

136
00:09:23,320 --> 00:09:25,719
Play it back if you need to.

137
00:09:25,719 --> 00:09:30,760
It's simple to say in a video, but in the real world, it requires lots of advocacy,

138
00:09:30,760 --> 00:09:33,400
communication, and work.

139
00:09:33,400 --> 00:09:35,200
And that's where you come in.

140
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:39,640
To learn more about bringing transformational literacy practices based on the science of

141
